In article <CF1w5F.IGI@vu-vlsi.ee.vill.edu>, kasturi@vu-vlsi.ee.vill.edu
(Srinivasa M. Kasturi - EE8460 Spring 1991) writes:
|> This may be a simple paper and pencil crypto
|> 
|> 	output
|> 	 ^
|> 	 |
|> 	-------
|> 	Reverse add
|> 	-----------
|> 	 ^	^
|> 	 |	| key3
|>   	 |	
|> 	--------
|> 	Add
|> 	-----------
|> 	 ^	^
|> 	 |	| key2
|> 	 |
|> 	--------
|> 	XOR
|> 	-----------
|> 	 ^	^
|> 	 |	| key1
|> 	data
|> 
|> Certianly requires careful choice of keys, that is non zero keys.
|> 
|> Further if data1 = data2 XOR data3
|> 	output1 <> output2 XOR output3
|> same is true for addition and reverse_addtion relation between inputs.
|> That is as of now I don't see any consistent relation(s) to exploit.
|> 
|> -- 
|> Disclaimer: Ideas expressed are my own and not those of either 
|> 	    my employer or my affiliations unless otherwise stated
|> kasturi@vu-vlsi.vill.edu  703-876-4444  kasturi@trwacs.fp.trw.com

This is effectively a monoalphabetic substitution, which tends to be
very weak.  In order to make it effective, you will need to increase
the size of the alphabet (block size) to make frequency counts 
impractical.

In addition, this will not tend to follow either the avalanche criteria,
or the non-linearity criteria, so it would probably be fairly easy to
crack, IMHO.

-David Mitchell
